<div id="review_1720230041" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1720230041" />
    <a title="Aj Sterkel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5790437-aj-sterkel"><img alt="Aj Sterkel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1450665689p2/5790437.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1720230041?book_show_action=true">Aug 05, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aj Sterkel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aj Sterkel" href="/user/show/5790437-aj-sterkel">Aj Sterkel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780803722903" href="/book/show/1351479.A_Long_Way_from_Chicago">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5790437-aj-sterkel?shelf=short-story-collection">short-story-collection</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1720230041" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer193934964997406860">This was a forced read for me. I needed a middlegrade book with an unusual narrative structure for a lecture Iâ€™m working on, and my mentor suggested this one. I had never heard of it before. Honestly, I groaned when I looked it up online because I have a love/hate relationship with middlegrade fiction. Some of it is brilliant, but a lot of it is too silly for my adult brain. The cover of this book looks juvenile. The synopsis sounds extremely juvenile. I braced myself to grit my teeth and plow t</span>
  <span id="freeText193934964997406860" style="display:none">This was a forced read for me. I needed a middlegrade book with an unusual narrative structure for a lecture Iâ€™m working on, and my mentor suggested this one. I had never heard of it before. Honestly, I groaned when I looked it up online because I have a love/hate relationship with middlegrade fiction. Some of it is brilliant, but a lot of it is too silly for my adult brain. The cover of this book looks juvenile. The synopsis sounds extremely juvenile. I braced myself to grit my teeth and plow through it . . .<br /><br />Iâ€™ve never been so surprised by a book.<br /><br /><i>A Long Way from Chicago</i> is a composite novel. Each of the nine chapters is a linked short story about Joey, Mary Alice, and their eccentric grandmother. The book starts in 1929, when Joey is nine years old, and ends in 1942, when heâ€™s eighteen. Each story is about an adventure he has when he leaves Chicago to spend a week in a rural town with Grandma.<br /><br />â€œAdventureâ€ again makes this book sound juvenile, but thatâ€™s the best word for it. The adventures are not unrealistic. Joey talks about the first time he sees a dead body, the first time he flies in a plane, and his desperate attempt to raise $2 for driving lessons. His grandmother helps him achieve his goals and learn important lessonsâ€”in her own bizarre way.<br /><br /><blockquote>â€œâ€˜Never trust an ugly woman. She's got a grudge against the world,' said Grandma, who was no oil painting herself.â€ â€“ <i>A Long Way from Chicago</i></blockquote><br /><br />The narratorâ€™s voice is what makes this book readable for adults. Joey is an old man looking back at his childhood, so the voice in all of the stories is mature. The author never talks down to the reader. Also, the stories have a very historical feel to them. Small-town 1930s life is captured in a vivid, believable way. The town is struggling with Depression-era poverty/alcoholism/trust issues, but the problems arenâ€™t shoehorned into the stories for educational purposes. The setting feels very natural. Iâ€™ve been reading a ton of historical fiction lately, and this little book is one of the better middlegrade historical novels Iâ€™ve read.<br /><br /><blockquote>â€œThe years went by, and Mary Alice and I grew up, slower than we wanted to, faster than we realized.â€ - <i>A Long Way from Chicago</i> </blockquote><br /><br />Grandma is eccentric, but never in a childlike, unrealistic way. Sheâ€™s actually one of the most complex adult characters Iâ€™ve come across in childrenâ€™s fiction. I totally believe a woman like Grandma could exist. She values her privacy and hates small-town gossip, but sheâ€™s not afraid to step in when something goes wrong. Sheâ€™s a strong woman who has a unique way of solving problems. Basically, sheâ€™s an elderly, cantankerous, Depression-era Robin Hood. <br /><br />I enjoyed every story in this book (which I donâ€™t say often about short story collections), but these are the standouts:<br /><br />In â€œShotgun Cheathamâ€™s Last Night Above Ground,â€ Grandma invents an impressive history for a man who died in poverty.<br /><br />â€œThe Day of Judgmentâ€ starts with Grandma reluctantly agreeing to enter a pie-making contest and ends with Grandma scamming her way onto an airplane.<br /><br />In â€œA One-Woman Crime Wave,â€ Grandma commits a series of small crimes in order to prepare a feast for the homeless drifters who wander through town.<br /><br /><blockquote>â€œI donâ€™t think Grandmaâ€™s a very good influence on us.â€ â€“ <i>A Long Way from Chicago</i></blockquote><br /><br />Iâ€™m struggling to come up with something I didnâ€™t like. I guess, for adult readers, the stories are a bit predictable and repetitive. They all follow the same basic outline: kids go to Grandmaâ€™s house; Grandma does something potentially deadly; the reader finds out that Grandma has a good reason for what she does. The repetition isnâ€™t a criticism, though, because this is a childrenâ€™s book, and I donâ€™t think I would have noticed it as a child. <br /><br /><i>A Long Way from Chicago</i> is a quick, entertaining read. I guess the lesson here is â€œDonâ€™t judge a book by its cover . . . or its synopsis.â€<br /></span>
